<div class="artwork-content">
    <div id="artwork-details">
        <div id="tombstone">
   
    <p><strong>01. Calumet New Town, Calumet, IN. "Air View of the Town" rendering, brochure, p.6, [1949].</strong><br />       1948-1949.
<br /><br />
The Calumet New Town plan, sponsored by General American Transportation Corporation CEO, Lester Selig, was conceived with the intent of creating a new, company town—in the spirit of Pullman, but "renewed"—from scratch. Selig's unorthodox plan was to retain ownership of the workingmen's houses by the company, yet with the explicit promise of a new home every worker, every 25 years.
<br /><br />
In this aerial plan of the town, the separation of zones by function—a hallmark of the planner Ludwig Hilberseimer, with whom Goldberg studied at the Bauhaus—is readily apparent. Hilberseimer's influence is also clear in the communities of residential "superblocks," buffered on two sides by open land. But rather than adopting Hilberseimer's process of "community formation through living patterns caused by sun, wind, or traffic," Goldberg sought out Le Corbisier's model of "community formation through humanism." The result was a plan that was to dramatically reduce the cost of living, including both food and transportation costs. More importantly, it intended to make a promise to workers that they "would not be faced with a constantly degenerating pattern of living."
<br /><br />
Unfortunately, insurance companies became afraid that such an large grouping of houses in a tightly-knit community could become the "tool of a rent strike in the event [the worker's] labor relations were unhappy" and declined to support the project, effectively killing it—though perhaps for good. Goldberg, in a later assessment of such "monolithic living" plans, found them less viable and attractive "for the later twentieth-century American life."<br /><br />
    	 "Architecture for Urbanism: Selections from the Bertrand Goldberg Archive," Case 8, Ryerson &amp; Burnham Libraries, November 1, 2011–January 2, 2012<br />
<br />
<a href="http://digital-libraries.saic.edu/u?/mqc,14869">Link to R&amp;B Archives Digital Collections record</a><br />    	    </p>

    </div><!--/tombstone-->
    </div><!--/artwork-details-->
